# TypeScript conventions

`tsconfig.json` runs with `strict`, `noUncheckedIndexedAccess`,
`exactOptionalPropertyTypes`, `verbatimModuleSyntax`, NodeNext modules.
Respect all of these — do not silence by widening types or adding
`@ts-ignore`.

## Banned without explicit justification

- `any`, `as any`, `as unknown as <T>` (unless there's a comment
  explaining why no narrower type works).
- `@ts-ignore`, `@ts-expect-error`.
- `console.log`, `console.error` in `src/shared/` and `src/main/`.
- `// TODO:`, `// FIXME:` in committed code. Either fix it or open an
  issue note in the relevant `.md`.

## Exports

- **Every exported symbol has TSDoc.** Functions, classes, interfaces,
  types, errors. Interfaces may put docs on fields instead of the
  interface itself, but exported functions and error classes always get
  a top-level doc comment.
- `verbatimModuleSyntax` is on: import types with `import type { … }`
  and re-export types with `export type …`.
- Relative imports inside `src/` end in `.js` (ESM + NodeNext).

## Errors and input validation

- Each module owns a named error class (e.g. `InvalidSizingInputError`,
  `InvalidPipValueInputError`). Don't throw bare `Error` for user-input
  failures.
- For every numeric parameter, a breaking test must cover NaN, Infinity,
  zero, negative, and any out-of-domain value (e.g. `riskPercent > 100`).
  The implementation must throw the module's error class for each case.
- Prefer pure, synchronous kernels for math. Callers in higher layers
  pass prices / rates in; kernels do no I/O.

## `src/shared/` additional rule

No imports from `src/main/`, `src/renderer/`, or any Electron / DOM API.
`shared` stays framework-free so tests can run without a DOM or Node
event loop. Only imports allowed: other `src/shared/*` modules and the
Node stdlib (sparingly).
